# Cursor Rules for Next.js App Router + Tailwind CSS

This configuration instructs Cursor to follow strict Next.js 14+ best practices.

## 1. Core Principles
- **Framework**: Next.js 14+ App Router.
- **Styling**: Tailwind CSS (no custom CSS classes unless absolutely necessary).
- **Icons**: Lucide React (`import { IconName } from 'lucide-react'`).
- **Components**: Functional components only. No class components.
- **Language**: TypeScript. Always use strict types. Avoid `any`.

## 2. File Structure & Naming
- **Routes**: Use the App Router file conventions: `page.tsx`, `layout.tsx`, `loading.tsx`, `error.tsx`, `not-found.tsx`.
- **Components**: Place reusable components in `@/components/ui` or `@/components/shared`.
- **Naming**:
    - Files: `kebab-case.tsx` (e.g., `user-card.tsx`).
    - Components: `PascalCase` (e.g., `UserCard`).
    - Utilities: `camelCase` (e.g., `formatDate.ts`).

## 3. Server vs. Client Components
- **Default behavior**: Assume all components are Server Components unless `useState`, `useEffect`, or event handlers are needed.
- **Client Directive**: Add `'use client'` at the *very top* of the file only when necessary.
- **Data Fetching**: Use Server Actions (`'use server'`) for mutations. Use `fetch` options (`{ next: { revalidate: 3600 } }`) for data caching strategy.

## 4. Coding Standards
- **Arrow Functions**: Use arrow functions (`const Component = () => {}`) for all components.
- **Props**: Destructure props in the function signature.
- **Imports**: Use absolute imports starting with `@/`.
    - `import { Button } from '@/components/ui/button'`
- **Tailwind**:
    - Use meaningful utility classes.
    - Group layout classes first (`flex`, `grid`, `absolute`), then sizing/spacing, then visuals (`bg-`, `text-`, `border-`).
    - Use `cn()` utility (from clsx/tailwind-merge) for conditional class names.

## 5. Typical Component Template
```tsx
import { cn } from "@/lib/utils";
import { MoveRight } from "lucide-react";

interface FeatureCardProps {
    title: string;
    description: string;
    className?: string;
}

export const FeatureCard = ({ title, description, className }: FeatureCardProps) => {
    return (
        <div className={cn("p-6 border rounded-lg hover:shadow-lg transition-shadow bg-card text-card-foreground", className)}>
            <h3 className="text-xl font-semibold mb-2 flex items-center gap-2">
                {title} <MoveRight className="w-4 h-4 text-muted-foreground" />
            </h3>
            <p className="text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
                {description}
            </p>
        </div>
    );
};
```

## 6. Error Handling
- Use `console.error` for catching errors in `try/catch` blocks but provide user-friendly feedback via toast notifications or error boundaries.
- Never swallow errors silently.

## 7. Performance
- Use `next/image` for all images providing `width`, `height`, and `alt`.
- Use `dynamic` imports for heavy client components (`next/dynamic`).
